r was born in 1969<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationaljournal.com/article/533128|title=NationalJournal|work=National Journal|accessdate=November 5, 2015}}</ref> in [[Dothan, Alabama]] and grew up in the panhandle of [[Florida]].  His father, an [[Independent Baptist]] minister, was the chaplain of a prison in Alabama, and brought his young son on his rounds. Walker recalled, \"I remember the joy on their faces that their lives matter, that somebody took the time to invest in them.\" There, \"he says he learned the lesson of acceptance, of 'looking beyond whatever social background, and just trying to see the person as an individual.'\"<ref name=\"wegmann\">{{cite web |url=http://dailysignal.com/2016/04/20/a-preacher-turned-lawmaker-and-his-new-campaign-to-win-the-old-war-on-poverty/ |title=A Preacher Turned Lawmaker and His New Campaign to Win the Old War on Poverty |last1=Wegmann |first1=Philip |date=April 20, 2016 |website=The Daily Signal |publisher=[[The Heritage Foundation]] |access-date=April 23, 2016}}</ref>\n\nWalker eventually attended [[Trinity Baptist College]] for a time before moving with his family to [[Houston, Texas]]. From there, Walker moved to the [[Piedmont Triad]]. He married Kelly Sears, a trauma nurse, and worked in business and finance for several years.<ref name=\"Vote Smart\">{{cite web |url=https://votesmart.org/candidate/biography/146255/mark-walker#.V85XjZMrKRs | title=Mark Walker Bio}}</ref>   Walker eventually returned to college to pursue the ministry and attend Piedmont Baptist College, now [[Piedmont International University]], graduating with a B.A. in Biblical Studies. Walker was ordained in the [[Southern Baptist]] denomination.  His career in ministry began at Calvary Baptist Church in Winston-Salem. From there he has worked for and led churches in North Carolina and Florida. He has served as a worship pastor, executive pastor and lead pastor.  In 2008, Walker started with Lawndale Baptist Church in [[Greensboro, North Carolina|Greensboro]] as its Pastor of Arts and Worship.<ref>[http://www.greensboro-nc.gov/modules/showdocument.aspx?documentid=18056 Biography and Resume at the City of Greensboro, North Carolina website]</ref>  The Walkers have three children and live in [[Guilford County, North Carolina|Guilford County]].\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n\n===Elections===\nWalker's 2014 campaign slogan was \"People Before Politics.\" Following the [[United States House of Representatives elections in North Carolina, 2014#District 6|primary election]], Walker and [[Phil Berger, Jr.]] advanced to a [[runoff election]]. Despite finishing second in the May primary, Walker unexpectedly won the runoff election by a significant margin.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/post-politics/wp/2014/07/15/baptist-minister-mark-walker-wins-republican-runoff-in-north-carolinas-6th-district/|title=Baptist minister Mark Walker wins Republican runoff in North Carolina\u2019s 6th District|author=Sean Sullivan|date=July 15, 2014|work=Washington Post|access-date=November 5, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\nIn Congress, Walker has focused on education reform, supporting domestic manufacturing, repealing Obamacare and limiting the size of government. He has also prioritized poverty and racial disparities in the local community.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://dailysignal.com/2016/07/14/what-we-can-learn-from-1-pastor-about-winning-the-war-on-poverty/ | title=What we can Learn from 1 past about Winning the War on Poverty}}</ref>\n\nWalker's first actions in office was to establish the Healthcare, Opportunity, Poverty and Education (H.O.P.E.) Commission for the 6th District and surrounding areas,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://walker.house.gov/media-center/press-releases/bringing-awareness-action-walker-launches-hope-commission |title=Bringing Awareness to Action: Walker Launches H.O.P.E. Commission |date=April 28, 2015 | website=Congressman Mark Walker |access-date=April 23, 2016}}</ref> determined in a 2015 [[Gallup (company)|Gallup]] survey and report to be the worst community in the nation for [[Hunger in the United States|food hardship]].<ref name=\"wegmann\"/>\n\nIn 2015 Rep. Walker introduced the Academic Partnerships Lead Us to Success (APLUS) amendment to the [[Student Success Act]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://walker.house.gov/media-center/press-releases/walker-fights-truly-return-control-education |title=Walker Fights to Truly Return Control of Education |date=July 8, 2015 | website=Congressman Mark Walker |access-date=April 23, 2016}}</ref>\n\n====HB2 Controversy====\nRep. Walker is a proponent of North Carolina's [[Public Facilities Privacy & Security Act]] (\"HB2\"), a controversial piece of legislation<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.charlotteobserver.com/news/politics-government/article68401147.html |title=Understanding HB2: North Carolina\u2019s newest law solidifies state\u2019s role in defining discrimination |last1=Gordon |first1=Michael |last2=Price |first2=Mark S. | last3=Peralta |first3=Katie |date=March 26, 2015 |publisher= [[The Charlotte Observer]] |access-date=April 23, 2016}}</ref> which was read, amended, passed and signed in a matter of hours on March 23, 2016.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ncleg.net/gascripts/BillLookUp/BillLookUp.pl?Session=2015E2&BillID=HB2 |title=House Bill 2 / S.L. 2016-3 Public Facilities Privacy & Security Act. 2016 Second Extra Session |author=North Carolina General Assembly |access-date=April 23, 2016}}</ref> On March 28, 2016, as businesses and local governments began registering opposition to HB2, Walker tweeted, \"I'm growing weary of the big business and corporate bullying over HB2.\"<ref>{{cite tweet |user=RepMarkWalker |number=714520443022082049 |date=March 28, 2016 |title=I'm growing weary of the big business and corporate bullying over HB2.}}</ref>   At a prayer breakfast on April 12, Walker expressed his opinion that the dismay and outrage over HB2 were \"part of a calculated strategy to retake control of the Senate, turn the state blue, and establish a base of support for the [2016] presidential election.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://dailysignal.com/2016/04/12/rep-mark-walker-liberals-exploiting-bathroom-bill-controversy-to-retake-north-carolina/ |title=Rep. Mark Walker: Liberals Exploiting Bathroom Bill Controversy for Political Gain |last1=Wegmann |first1=Philip |date=April 12, 2016 |website=[[The Daily Signal]] |publisher=[[The Heritage Foundation]] |access-date=April 23, 2016}}</ref>\n\n====2014 Remarks on Border Security and War with Mexico====\nDuring his 2014 campaign, at a [[Tea Party movement|Tea Party]] forum in [[Rockingham County, North Carolina]], Walker was asked if military force was appropriate along the US-Mexican border. He stated that the [[National Guard of the United States|National Guard]] might be necessary to secure the border.<ref name=Record>{{cite news|title=War With Mexico? Of Course Not|url=http://www.news-record.com/news/walker-war-with-mexico-of-course-not/article_eeb349fa-3f9e-11e4-8089-001a4bcf6878.html|accessdate=September 19, 2014|publisher=News-Record|date=September 19, 2014}}</ref> He added, \"...if you have foreigners who are sneaking in with drug cartels, to me that is a national threat, and if we got to go laser or blitz somebody.. I don\u2019t have a problem with that either.\" The moderator then asked if he had any qualms about starting a war with Mexico. Walker responded jokingly, \"Well, we did it before, if we need to do it again, I don't have a qualm about it.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsobserver.com/2014/09/18/4162234/republican-mark-walker-no-qualms.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=November 7, 2014 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141110123131/http://www.newsobserver.com/2014/09/18/4162234/republican-mark-walker-no-qualms.html |archivedate=November 10, 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wral.com/walker-he-doesn-t-have-a-qualm-about-war-with-mexico/13995217/ |title=Walker doesn't 'have a qualm' about war with Mexico |last1=Binker |first1=Mark |date=September 19, 2014 |website=WRAL.com |publisher=[[WRAL-TV]] |access-date=April 10, 2016}}</ref> Later, Walker met with the editors of the ''[[Greensboro News & Record]]'' to tell them, \"Being someone who is not a career politician, I\u2019ve learned there are different environments that are a little more heated in context. And when you walk into those by proxy, you have to be very concerned as well as being very upfront about what your positions are because you can be guided very easily.\"<ref name=\"killian\">{{cite web |url=http://www.greensboro.com/news/government/elections/will-the-real-mark-walker-step-up/article_3c5b3500-46c0-11e4-ba80-001a4bcf6878.html |title=Will the real Mark Walker step up? |last1=Killian |first1=Joe |date=September 27, 2014 |website=[[Greensboro News & Record]] |access-date=April 23, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Committee assignments==\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Homeland Security|Committee on Homeland Security]]'''\n** [[United States House Homeland Security Subcommittee on Emergency Preparedness, Response, and Communications|Subcommittee on Emergency Preparedness, Response, and Communications]]\n**[[United States House Homeland Security Subcommittee on Transportation Security|Subcommittee on Transportation Security]]\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Oversight and Government Reform|Committee on Oversight and Government Reform]]'''\n** [[United States House Oversight Subcommittee on Information Technology]]\n*'''[[United States House Committee on House Administration]]'''\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.walker.house.gov Official House website]\n* [http://www.walker4nc.com Mark Walker for Congress]\n* [http://www.newsobserver.com/2014/12/16/4407188/nc-pols-make-gq-list-of-20-craziest.html ''NC Lawmakers Make GQ's List of 20 Craziest Politicians'']\n* {{C-SPAN|bradleywalker}}\n{{CongLinks | congbio = W000